# Goal

Study the trajectory: infer what changes helped, what hurt, and where the current best prompt still fails.
Metric descriptions state the rubric; scores and judge reasons on prior steps reveal what the template still leaves implicit.
Infer that missing rubric and encode it in the new template so the model is steered toward higher scores.
Then write an improved prompt template.
You may refine the best checkpoint or explore a completely different approach.
You may add, edit or remove instructions to study their effect, or rewrite the template entirely from scratch.

Keep every Jinja placeholder (enclosed in double curly braces) from the templates above exactly as-is (same names and syntax).
Removing or renaming them breaks rendering and makes the template unusable.

If the real bottleneck lies outside the template, you can record it additionally as an advice for human review.
These can be:
- Changes in the output schema fields or their descriptions
- Deterministic pre-/post-processing around the completion
- The model seems uncapable to adhere to the instructions
- The example data is flawed, contradictory or plainly wrong
You must still explore different options in any of these scenarios.
